Question: How do I return e-books early
Answer: Answer:  Yes, you can return OverDrive eBooks early by using Adobe Digital Editions. If you're using an OverDrive app on a device, you can return early using the app.    Step 1   Bring up Adobe Digital Editions,   Step 2   Make sure you are in the Library View ( the row of books icon below the Adobe Digital Editions icon)  Step 2   Mouse over the book cover you want to return  Step 3   There is an arrow to the left called “Item Options”, click on it  Step 4   The 4th item down is “Return borrowed item", click on it  Step 5   A message will pop up and ask "Are you sure you want to return borrowed item"  Step 6   Click return and the item is returned to the library.

Question: Lookinfor for information on the number of mental health facilities in the United States
Answer: The most recent census data I can find is from 2007. Information about how many of a particular business can be found in the economic census.    Here is the information I found:  Outpatient mental health and substance abuse centers - http://www.census.gov/econ/industry/geo/g621420.htm  Psychiatric and substance abuse hospitals - http://www.census.gov/econ/industry/geo/g622210.htm  Residential mental health and substance abuse facilities - http://www.census.gov/econ/industry/geo/g623220.htm    If you click on the Definition tab it will explain the distinctions they make between the categories.  The Historical tab has data for the past couple economic census if you are interested in seeing the change over time. Unfortunately  this data doesn't go very far back as they redefined things in 1997. You can look at data before that, but they way they defined and split things is different.

Question: I am writing a research paper in my 100W class and I wanted to know how to cite my personal story in the introduction in APA format? I have been looking everywhere and have not found an answer yet. Should I even put a personal story in? If there is no way to cite the personal story, how would I include my story in?
Answer: Since you're the author, you don't have to cite your personal story.  Citing is necessary if you're writing something that is can be disproved.  Basically, you're providing a citation for your reader to check on the sources that you consulted.  If this is a personal story, no one can really check the veracity of your statements.  In terms of how you treat it in your paper you can write in the body of the paper something like, "The author experienced this situation as a child..."      Now, if you were conducting an interview or had corresponded with someone, then you would cite in-text the name of the individual, indicate that it was personal communication, and note the date.  See this example from the OWL at Purdue.      http://owl.english.purdue.edu/owl/resource/560/11/    I hope this helps!  Let me know if you have any further questions.

Question: I am a social work student needing help finding references for an assignment. The topic is the effectivesness of treating a domestic violence victim with cognitive behavioral therapy.
Answer: I would do searches on the topic in the following databases:  PsycINFO        Social Sciences Full Text        Social Services Abstracts        Sociological Abstracts        SocINDEX with FullText          PsychINFO covers CBT pretty thoroughly, so you should be able to find enough to support that side of your paper. It looks like some of the other databases place CBT under the broader heading of cognitive therapy, so you may need to try a few different search methodologies to find what you need. Switch out the following in the databases if you don't think you are finding what you need: CBT, Cognitive Behavior Therapy, Cognitive Behavior Treatment, Cognitive behavioral, and Cognitive therapy.  For domestic violence you may also need to switch out the terms in different databases, e.g. domestic violence or domestic abuse or family violence.

Question: I am a student at San Jose State University studying abroad at a design school in Germany.  I am taking a Theorie class here that will be transferrable to a couple upper-division art history courses.  I need some help.  I need to find a book or articles relating to why designers choose to design something modern.  Or what is modern?  The psychology behind Contemporary design.  As well as California Architecture.  Do you have any suggestions?
Answer: I'll be happy to help you.  First of all, do you know your student id  and library pin?  If so, you will be able to access the full text  journal article databases on this webpage:     http://libguides.sjsu.edu/design    The databases that are likely to be most helpful to you are Art Full  Text and JSTOR.  Within those databases, citations that are not full  text have a link marked "Get Text" that will link to our databases.    You will probably need to narrow your topic down somewhat, or maybe  you have two separate questions.  Are you researching designers or  architects?  And, are you looking at commercial or domestic  architecture.    Here's an example of a citation that is about an article that  discusses the architect Joseph Eichler and his impact on California  architecture:      Solomon, Daniel  Source:  Places: Forum of Design for the Public Realm; Fall2001, Vol. 14 Issue  2, p38-45, 8p    Subjects:  California; Eichler, Joseph; American architecture -- History -- 20th  century; Dwellings -- History; Domestic architecture; Open plan  (Building)  Abstract:  The writer discusses the postwar houses designed by Joseph Eichler.  Eichler's formula for his houses was comprised in equal parts of the  Case Study House, a fantasy housing program during the war, and  Levittown, Long Island, a model of rationalized mass production of  housing for the G.I. Bill. While his houses looked like modest  versions of the Case Study Houses, their timber, plywood, light wood  framing and particle board, were more like the houses of Levittown.    http://libaccess.sjlibrary.org/login?url=http://search.ebscohost.com/login.aspx?direct=true&db=aft&AN=504979556&site=ehost-live    Another way to investigate the topic is to look at the corporations  that were forming and their methods.  Here's an article that discusses  several examples:    Journal of Design History Volume 19, Issue 3Pp. 233-248  This Year's Model  Representing Modernism to the Post-war American Corporation  http://jdh.oxfordjournals.org.libaccess.sjlibrary.org/content/19/3/233.full?sid=8f7be0e7-d2ef-467e-a980-9e37465251a8    Please write back with more thoughts about what you would like to  find, and also whether or not the above links let you see the full  text of the articles.

Items will be held for 7 days on a self-service hold-shelf at your chosen library  You will be charged a $3 fee for every hold that is not picked up after 7 days  Receive notification (in English) by email or phone when the item you requested is available  Monitor the status of your requests online in your Library Account or by phone at 1-408-808-BOOK (808-2665). Question: How do I return Kindle books early?
Answer: How to Return a Kindle eBook early    1. An eBook checked out on the Kindle is returned through Amazon. Got to www.amazon.com and from the Kindle menu on the right select “Manage Your Kindle”.  2. Sign into your Amazon account.  3. Select the “Actions” drop down menu next to the took you want to return; the words public library will appear next to any library eBooks.  4. From the menu select “Return this book” make sure to avoid selecting “Delete from library” as this will delete the book from your Kindle Library but WILL NOT RETURN IT.  5. Select “Yes” to return the book  6. After you return the book it will still show in Your Kindle Library list. To remove it from the list, select Actions again, and from the dropdown menu select “Delete from library”

I am also copying Ron Liu, our IT person in Biology.
Answer: Yes, the library has a proxy URL.  It's     http://libaccess.sjlibrary.org/login?url=    I've heard a lot of good things about Cubic Reader.  I haven't tried it yet, though.  If you use Google Scholar fairly often, I would also recommend that you set up your Google Scholar Library Links preferences to include the SJSU GetText link.  This will connect you to our holdings when you're in Google Scholar.  An advantage of using Google Scholar is that often author pre-prints or institutional repository holdings are available for immediate use, as opposed to the regular library databases, which only search for the publisher copy.

Question: How do I easily find e-books on SJPL.com that will work on my kindle.. Also, how do I avoid being shifted to various websites while searching where I have to constantly have to RE-log in with my Library # & PIN?

You will need to download the software first to your computer before you will be able to access  the materials and you will also need a valid library card and and pin number. You will also notice a Need Help section on this page with frequently asked questions and tips. You can also try checking your Kindle account on Amazon for the title and then send it to your Kindle manually. If it's not there, you will need to log in to your OverDrive account and send it over again.    Here are the instructions that can be found at                    http://help.overdrive.com/article/0431/How-to-borrow-Kindle-Books-from-your-library    Here is information on the acsm file                     http://help.overdrive.com/article/0577/What-are-ODM-and-ACSM-files
